# Walkthrough: PRISM Base Mode Implementation

We have successfully designed, implemented, and compiled the **PRISM Base Mode** configuration. This mode leverages the global environment flag `PRISM_BASE_MODE=true` to adjust hardware utilization parameters, orchestrate on-demand GGUF sequential slot reclaiming, check and lock Ollama residents in graphics memory, and prune the Guardian task execution catalog to match the resource profile of a **GTX 1050 Ti VRAM** and **Core i5 Haswell CPU**.

---

## Changes Made

### 1. Hardware-Level `llama-server` Optimization Flags
**File modified**: [llama-cpp-supervisor.ts](file:///d:/Projects/Prism/src/core/operator/llama-cpp-supervisor.ts)
- Checked `process.env.PRISM_BASE_MODE === "true"` when spawning processes.
- Clamped context windows strictly to **2048** to keep memory allocation low.
- Enforced `--threads 4` to match physical i5 cores and bypass thread-scheduling context overhead.
- Enforced `--batch-size 64` to maximize CPU L3 cache hits.
- Bypassed draft-model specular decoding to reclaim graphics memory.
- Enforced full GPU offload `--n-gpu-layers 99` and `--flash-attn` to accelerate inference and bypass slow system memory buses.
- Implemented DDR3 prefix caching with `--grp-attn-n 1 --grp-attn-w 512` arguments for instant in-memory context swapping.

### 2. Dynamic Ollama Interrogation & Keep-Alive Locking
**File modified**: [llm-provider-manager.ts](file:///d:/Projects/Prism/src/core/operator/llm-provider-manager.ts)
- Added private helper `isOllamaModelHot(settings, modelName)` which makes a lightweight `/api/ps` check.
- If Ollama indicates the model is hot/resident in VRAM, requests are dispatched with `keep_alive: -1` to lock it in memory and avoid frequent unloading.
- Standardized context clamping to 2048 for Ollama generations in Base Mode.

### 3. Single-Slot Sequential Runner (SSSR) Dynamic Loading
**File modified**: [llm-provider-manager.ts](file:///d:/Projects/Prism/src/core/operator/llm-provider-manager.ts)
- In the `generate` pipeline, if the active provider is `llamacpp` and the GGUF supervisor slot does not hold the model, SSSR auto-loading takes over.
- Resolves the model path and executes `loadModel(...)` on the supervisor, awaiting slot availability and initialization before routing the OpenAI-compatible completion request.

### 4. Guardian Task Catalog Pruning
**File modified**: [guardian-agent.ts](file:///d:/Projects/Prism/src/core/agents/guardian-agent.ts)
- In the Guardian constructor, if `PRISM_BASE_MODE === "true"`, the catalog is pruned of resource-heavy diagnostic tasks.
- Only the **survival triad** is registered:
  1. `directive_integrity` (SHA-256 validation of directives)
  2. `mcp_health_recovery` (Tool adapters self-healing)
  3. `aab_ledger_monitor` (Anomalous autonomous loop circuit breaker)

### 5. System Boot Validation Logs
**File modified**: [index.ts](file:///d:/Projects/Prism/src/index.ts)
- Injected clear boot logging so the operator knows exactly when the active resource constraint paradigm is active:
  ```
  [PRISM][startup] ======================================================
  [PRISM][startup] ACTIVE CONSTRAINT PARADIGM ENGAGED: Base Mode initialized.
  [PRISM][startup] Optimizing GGUF and task scheduling for GTX 1050 Ti & Core i5 Haswell.
